 {"id":"charmed_rust-5x5","title":"Comprehensive Conformance Testing & Feature Parity Verification","description":"# Overview

This epic establishes comprehensive conformance testing between our Rust ports and the original Go Charm libraries. The goal is threefold:

1. **Deep-Dive Cross-Section Analysis**: Randomly sample critical algorithms from Go source and verify Rust implementations match semantically
2. **Conformance Harness**: Build a unified testing framework that serves as E2E tests, benchmarks, and feature parity proof
3. **Comprehensive Logging**: Every test provides detailed, actionable output for debugging and verification

## Background & Motivation

We have ported 8 Charm Go libraries to Rust:
- **harmonica**: Spring/projectile physics animations
- **lipgloss**: Terminal styling (colors, borders, layout)  
- **bubbletea**: Elm Architecture TUI framework
- **bubbles**: TUI components (viewport, textinput, list, table, filepicker, etc.)
- **charmed_log**: Structured logging
- **glamour**: Markdown rendering
- **huh**: Interactive forms
- **wish**: SSH application framework

While unit tests exist, we lack systematic verification that behaviors match the Go originals. This is critical because:
- Users migrating from Go expect identical behavior
- Edge cases may differ subtly
- Performance characteristics should be comparable

## Architecture

### Conformance Harness Design
```
tests/conformance/
├── harness/           # Shared test infrastructure
│   ├── mod.rs         # Harness framework
│   ├── logging.rs     # Detailed test logging
│   ├── benchmark.rs   # Benchmark utilities
│   └── comparison.rs  # Output comparison utilities
├── fixtures/          # Test data and expected outputs
│   ├── go_outputs/    # Captured Go behavior
│   └── inputs/        # Shared test inputs
├── harmonica/         # Per-crate conformance tests
├── lipgloss/
├── bubbletea/
├── bubbles/
├── charmed_log/
├── glamour/
├── huh/
└── wish/
```

### Test Categories Per Crate
1. **Unit Conformance**: Individual function behavior matches
2. **Integration**: Component interactions work correctly
3. **Edge Cases**: Boundary conditions, error handling
4. **Performance**: Benchmarks against baseline expectations

### Logging Philosophy
- Every test logs: inputs, expected outputs, actual outputs, diffs
- Hierarchical logging with test context
- Machine-parseable format for CI integration
- Human-readable summaries

## Success Criteria

- [ ] All 8 crates have comprehensive conformance suites
- [ ] Deep-dive cross-sections documented for core algorithms
- [ ] Benchmark baselines established
- [ ] E2E integration tests cover common workflows
- [ ] CI-ready test harness with excellent logging","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","owner":"jeff141421@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-01-17T10:48:15.274350093-05:00","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-01-18T05:09:22.730690679-05:00","closed_at":"2026-01-18T05:09:22.730690679-05:00","close_reason":"All 12 sub-tasks completed: harness framework, Go reference capture, all 8 crate conformance suites (harmonica, lipgloss, bubbletea, bubbles, charmed_log, glamour, huh, wish), cross-crate integration tests (24 tests), and CI report generation. Final status: 481/541 tests passing (89%), 53 skipped, 7 failing (all in mouse parsing)."}
 {"id":"charmed_rust-5x5.1","title":"Build Conformance Harness Framework","description":"# Build Conformance Harness Framework

## Purpose
Create the foundational testing infrastructure that all per-crate conformance tests will use. This framework must be:
- Reusable across all 8 crates
- Self-documenting with excellent logging
- Capable of benchmarking
- Able to compare outputs systematically

## Technical Design

### Module Structure
```rust
// tests/conformance/harness/mod.rs
pub mod logging;
pub mod benchmark;
pub mod comparison;
pub mod fixtures;
pub mod reports;
```

### Core Components

#### 1. ConformanceTest Trait
```rust
/// Trait implemented by each conformance test
pub trait ConformanceTest {
    /// Human-readable name
    fn name(&self) -> &str;

    /// Which crate this tests
    fn crate_name(&self) -> &str;

    /// Category: unit, integration, edge_case, performance
    fn category(&self) -> TestCategory;

    /// Execute the test with logging context
    fn run(&self, ctx: &mut TestContext) -> TestResult;

    /// Optional benchmark variant
    fn benchmark(&self, ctx: &mut BenchContext) -> Option<BenchResult> {
        None
    }
}
```

#### 2. TestContext with Rich Logging
```rust
pub struct TestContext {
    logger: TestLogger,
    fixtures: FixtureLoader,
    comparator: OutputComparator,
}

impl TestContext {
    /// Log an input being tested
    pub fn log_input<T: Debug>(&mut self, name: &str, value: &T);

    /// Log expected output (from Go reference)
    pub fn log_expected<T: Debug>(&mut self, name: &str, value: &T);

    /// Log actual output (from Rust)
    pub fn log_actual<T: Debug>(&mut self, name: &str, value: &T);

    /// Compare and log diff
    pub fn assert_eq<T: PartialEq + Debug>(&mut self, expected: &T, actual: &T) -> bool;

    /// Log subsection (nested context)
    pub fn section<F>(&mut self, name: &str, f: F) where F: FnOnce(&mut TestContext);
}
```

#### 3. Logging System
```rust
pub struct TestLogger {
    level: LogLevel,
    output: Box<dyn Write>,
    indent: usize,
    timestamps: bool,
}

// Output format:
// [2025-01-17T10:30:00Z] [INFO] lipgloss::render_test
//   Input:
//     style: Style { fg: Color::Red, bold: true }
//     text: "Hello, World!"
//   Expected:
//     "\x1b[31;1mHello, World!\x1b[0m"
//   Actual:
//     "\x1b[31;1mHello, World!\x1b[0m"
//   Result: PASS (0.003ms)
```

#### 4. Benchmark Framework
```rust
pub struct BenchContext {
    warmup_iterations: usize,
    measure_iterations: usize,
    results: Vec<Duration>,
}

pub struct BenchResult {
    name: String,
    min: Duration,
    max: Duration,
    mean: Duration,
    median: Duration,
    std_dev: Duration,
    iterations: usize,
}
```

#### 5. Output Comparison
```rust
pub struct OutputComparator {
    /// Compare strings with ANSI escape normalization
    pub fn compare_ansi(&self, expected: &str, actual: &str) -> CompareResult;

    /// Compare floating point with epsilon
    pub fn compare_f64(&self, expected: f64, actual: f64, epsilon: f64) -> CompareResult;

    /// Compare complex structures with detailed diff
    pub fn compare_debug<T: Debug>(&self, expected: &T, actual: &T) -> CompareResult;
}

pub enum CompareResult {
    Equal,
    Different { expected: String, actual: String, diff: String },
    ApproximatelyEqual { delta: f64, epsilon: f64 },
}
```

### File Organization
```
tests/conformance/
├── harness/
│   ├── mod.rs           # Re-exports
│   ├── test_trait.rs    # ConformanceTest trait
│   ├── context.rs       # TestContext implementation
│   ├── logging.rs       # TestLogger with formatting
│   ├── benchmark.rs     # BenchContext and BenchResult
│   ├── comparison.rs    # OutputComparator
│   ├── fixtures.rs      # FixtureLoader
│   └── reports.rs       # Summary report generation
├── Cargo.toml           # Test crate dependencies
└── lib.rs               # Conformance test library
```

## Implementation Steps

1. Create `tests/conformance/` directory structure
2. Implement `TestLogger` with hierarchical output
3. Implement `TestContext` with logging integration
4. Implement `OutputComparator` with diff generation
5. Implement `BenchContext` with statistical analysis
6. Implement `FixtureLoader` for test data
7. Implement `ConformanceTest` trait
8. Create report generation for CI
9. Write unit tests for the harness itself
10. Create example conformance test demonstrating usage

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Harness compiles and passes its own tests
- [ ] Logging produces readable, parseable output
- [ ] Benchmarks produce accurate statistical results
- [ ] Comparison correctly identifies differences
- [ ] Example test demonstrates full workflow
- [ ] Documentation explains usage patterns

## Dependencies

None - this is the foundation.

